Today is my 3 year Trail-versary!

It's a day that will always be special to me for the rest of my life. It's sort of like my second birthday. I guess because my experience out there in those mountains was very much like a re-birth for me. Sitting in the dirt, on a mountain, writing this, I realize some things don't change. I think about the trail every single damn day. It's a part of me. And to this day, I'm still uncovering little wisdom nuggets and changes within me that occurred out there.

I think about the man I was 4 years ago, about to depart on that journey. Neve, green, a head full of steam, eyes wide. I think about what I'd tell him. What he'd need to know of the joys and perils that lie ahead. How his life was about to be shattered wide open in a way that the original pieces would never quite fit back together the same. But then I stop...

...and I realize, I wouldn't give him that advice even if I could. Because rewatching him learn how to talk with his feet, and follow his heart into vast unknowns is far too valuable an experience, and overall, just extremely entertaining to watch.

I admit it has taken all of these 3 years to get to a place where I can smile, with all of myself, about the trail. It has been so much to unpack mentally. I want to thank ANYONE who has ever endured one of my trail stories. I know that I can get a bit "this one time at band camp" with the whole thing, but for real, it's been one of the best therapies for me. I have so many stories! It's most of what I have. And I treasure that.

Ya ya, lazy me. I still have a 195 GB of trail media content that has yet to materialize into what I envisioned. But my vision has evolved quite a bit by now. Still chewing on some ideas. I know there are people out there that would like to see what I have.

Anyway, Cheers! And if I can just tell you one thing today....

NEVER be afraid to scare the shit out of yourself and have big, beautiful goals. Things don't always go "correctly", but I promise you, if you are following your heart, it will work out in the most unexpected and beautiful ways ‚ù§‚ù§‚ù§

As always, Your Friendly Neighborhood,

(((RIPPLE)))

A year ago I wrote a tiny page for my country and, most importantly, I added a huge chapter in my book of life.
I started this adventure as a guy with many unanswered questions and few solid certainties. I ended as a man who faces fears, dreams big and is curious enough to discover what‚Äôs beyond his limits.
That‚Äôs why today I carry this experience with deep love but also with an understanding that memories are great only if we build on them, because the future offers endless blank pages awaiting to be filled with amazing stories.

To stand atop this mountain changed my life forever. 7/19/2018
.
.
It created a vision of possibility which has made civilized reality tough to swallow. It empowered independence and tribe in me simultaneously. It highlighted the importance of simplicity, faith and novelty as a recipe for my own happiness. It did soo much while doing soo little, implying that the real changes happened within.
.
.
It's been one helluva year since this day, and in honesty it hasn't been all good. Post trail depression is real. Feeling helpless in a crumbling world after having been shown the steady symbiosis of nature. Confronted with the unsustainable pillage of our natural lands and the artificial identities we're promoted to assume. It's hard to come back and pretend like everything is okay. I have a home and a job, I have abundant food and potable water, but what are the impacts of these blessings?
.
.
Thruhiking was a gift which shattered some paradigms and reinforced others. Its given me tools to navigate the internal landscape, and in soo many ways has enriched my life. But I wanted to be real today, it wasn't all great. I smiled on that summit with joy of accomplishment, while battling the sinking feeling of having to reenter a society I dont agree with. To thruhike perpetually would be to avoid reality, but I struggle with how to integrate these two worlds...
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

Last year I was the 135th NOBO to hit the ATC in Harper's Ferry. Now, back in the real world I find myself recalling these moments on the daily. Trying to integrate these trail lessons in my current life, today's lesson is that process > destination. Don't let self-criticism and doubt cloud the way to your literal or metaphorical Katadhin. Your journey has very little to do with that summit. At the end, you'll howl at the moon atop that sign not because you've finished, but because of everything you've done in between. Enjoy the process!
.

.

Appalachian Trail 2018 - Day 49. Leaving Pearisburg on the way to Rice Field shelter. Had a restful zero day (zero miles hiked) in town and back into the pouring rain. The night was spent hiding in the shelter as it torrentially downpoured. No pictures from the follow day when we had to walk through water up to our knees, through raging stream crossings, and finish the day in snow and freezing temperatures. Open your shoes up wide before you fall asleep, you'll thank yourself when you slip on those ice cubes in the morning. (Poo trowels work very well as shoe horns #deuceofspades)

It's been roughly 5 months since I touched the summit of Katadhin, and it's surreal. In this same period of time 5 months earlier I moved my body through 14 states, ascended roughly 500,000 cumulative feet, made amazing friends, and forged unforgettable memories. I slept under the stars, swam in beautiful lakes, chafed until my butt cheeks bled, and loved every single moment. Now back in the real world I'm already planning the next one. So to all those planning their first thru, and those planning another, here's to another year of new friends and chafed butt cheeks!!

GA->ME over!
I just finished #thruhiking the most iconic long distance #trail in the world! The @appalachiantrail was such a rollercoaster. Mentally and physically it pushed me to the very brink. None of my previous hikes brutalized me this way. It was absolutely sadistic at times - had me schlepping through miles of pure rock, tripping over roots, bouldering up sheer mountain faces - I got scraped and stabbed; ended up face planting in the dirt more times than I can count; I screamed and cried and cursed the gods for putting me through such hell - and just as many times I laughed my ass off with my incredible trail family - @rebecca.harnish, @moronman, @austincolelambert_jinx, @garrettvandeperre and Crypto - creating ridiculous inside jokes throughout the course of 14 states. And, throughout the 5+ months I met some of the most amazing people you could ever meet. That's the thing about thru-hiking - once you're in it and you meet this insane motley crew of characters, you wonder how if you had waited a year or gone a year earlier, how they wouldn't be in your life. And that's pretty damn impossible to imagine, especially now that this incredible adventure is over. To all you beautiful souls I met on this wild ride - thank you for sharing your stories and your love with me. To all my friends and family who supported me through this - I can't thank you enough. It starts by testing your body. Your muscles, your joints. Your calves scream thinking at the next climb.
Then it fucks with your mind. The green tunnel, the constant repetition of every movement, the never ending rain. The loneliness.
At last though, it touches your soul. The sudden realization of what you‚Äôve just accomplished is almost too much to handle. Mind and body come together and time stops. It‚Äôs inner peace, calm ecstasy.
After all, thru-hiking the Appalachian Trail it‚Äôs not just a journey, it‚Äôs a revelation. üìù

Day 149: I ended my hike today. I had had enough of the rain. I‚Äôd been crying more than smiling over the past few weeks. Hiking wasn‚Äôt fun anymore, and I‚Äôd actually gotten what I came for months ago. I made the best friends I could ask for, and saw incredible parts of my country via my two feet. I am incredibly proud of myself for my accomplishments this spring and summer. And I‚Äôd like to think this beast didn‚Äôt break me completely- I‚Äôd still like to come back sometime and give it a try southbound. But for now, it‚Äôs time to start working on the next chapter of my life. To my friends still out there- I admire each of you so much! Stay in touch! #smidgehikestheat #atnobo2018 #appalachiantrail2018 #mtkatahdin #sowindy #crushedit #hadablast

It's been a week and a half since finishing, and my body is just now starting to feel normal again. The day-to-day grind took a much larger toll than I ever anticipated--my knees and feet have required more rest than I've ever given them before. Thinking back, it's these aches and pains that hikers tolerate everyday that make it all worth it. They fill moments like these, when I crossed back into Maine, with a euphoria I only dreamed of prior.

Holy guacamole! We have been in the White Mountains for the last few days and they are fabulous. Rocky, vertical and inspiring. Franconia Ridge was gorgeous and we have been so fortunate to have excellent weather for the days we have summited. We hiked the Presidential range yesterday, we summited Eisenhower, Washington, and Madison. The AT only lends itself to summiting Washington and Madison but in our excitement we went up and over Eisenhower, too. Last night we did a work for stay at the Madison Springs hut. The crew was so fun, and we had a terrific meal and washed dishes and scraped the freezer of ice in return for the meal and the opportunity to sleep inside. This hut has the best sunset and sunrise views and was the first of the huts to be built by the AMC in the White‚Äôs. Today we climbed up and over Mt Madison and down through Pinkham Notch and then back up and over the Wildcats and then back down near the Carter Notch hut where we met a few of the hut crew and had a hearty bowl of stew and some delicious treats compliments of the hut master. We are having the best time!!!!! #atnobo2018 #appalachiantrail #appalachiantrail2018 #thetrailprovides #nobo2018

Wow. Okay. Wow. What an incredible, humbling, beautiful mountain. Before I say anything else, I need to say thanks to some special people who made this whole thing possible. Thank you to my parents, who supported me in my journey from the moment I told them I intended to thru hike nearly 4 years ago. A big shout out to my resupply guy Kenny Shapiro, for helping me switch out my gear just when I needed it most. And finally, a HUGE thank you to all the trail angels who provided any form of trail magic--your incredible generosity inspires me to be a better human. Words cannot describe my strong feelings of affection for this trail and the amazing people who inhabited it this spring/summer. You made my journey spectacular; I hope our paths cross again soon. For some reason, I got a good feeling this isn't my last thru hike üòè

Moving through the week like...‚òÅÔ∏èWe are off trail for a few days to rest and restore. I was reflecting on all of the love, support, thoughts, prayers, and hoorays all y‚Äôall have given to us. I am missing each of you and that might be one of the hardest parts of taking on a task such as this, being away from those you love the most while pursuing a dream that is physically and mentally tasking. But I close my eyes and I picture the time and care you have spent with me, talking about your own dreams and how worth it is to follow through. Thank you for being here with me, your love and kindness are making it easier to be away a bit longer. We hiked into Vermont yesterday night! We both loved hiking in Massachusetts, the terrain and forests were perfect. Though we are sad to be through the state we are over joyed to be in VT. 1600 miles now hiked, three states in front of us with the mountains ahead and so many good memories and sweet people behind us. We watched the sunset tonight front a fire tower at the top of Glastenbury Mountain, and we could see those mountains growing higher in that blue of distance. It is daunting, it is exciting, it is what we‚Äôve been waiting for. The river was a welcome respite earlier in our day, we soaked our feet and knees before we started a big climb. At the beginning of our day we saw this big ole frog who never moved the entire time we were near him, a perfect photo subject and the last photo was from yesterday atop Mt Greylock, the highest point in Massachusetts. #appalachiantrail #appalachiantrail2018 #atnobo2018 #nobo2018 #womenwhohike #hike

Day 99: Mile 1,107 - Not only did we pass the half way point, and 1,100 miles today.. we also experienced our first rain in Pennsylvania, followed by a very close encounter with a black rattlesnake! While passing through a very narrow path along rocks and roots our buddy Stretch spotted this young fella digesting away on this nice warm rock. Just in time, mind you because this photo was NOT zoomed in. The path was just on top of the rock to the left of the snake. We all froze just in time and backed up. The snake never rattled at us, but did raise his tail a few times as a warming, and moved his head. We were frozen like statues and there was no way to walk around or off trail, we had to walk past him. Thankfully a hiker behind us was a little bit more daring and offered to walk past first, and stand in front as we all sneaked pass. üò¨ We have been warned many times that this section of the trail is known for their snakes, and so far this has been very true. Today over our 18.4 mile day we saw a total of three snakes, thankfully only one poisonous! This guy we won‚Äôt forget. #appalachiantrail #appalachiantrail2018 #atthruhike #atnobo2018 #atthruhike2018 #hikerlife #hiketheat #georgiatomaine  #rattlesnake

Since Harper's Ferry, I have been pushing hard everyday to see what my body and spirit are capable of accomplishing. Over the last 18 days, I put in a little over 425 miles on the trail (~23.6 average per day). Now, it's time for a break. Tomorrow I'll take my first zero of the last 800 miles and relax at the house of Gruber @parmigiano_jono and Sunday I'll zero again to visit friends in NYC. My body is pretty spent, but nothing a little bit of a lazy weekend can't heal. After a much needed recharge, I'll be off to explore the remaining 1/3 of the trail!

Day 75: Since leaving the hostel last weekend, there has been hardly any rain! Yay! It had rained every day so far that I have been in this state! The lows have definitely gotten worse, though: we had to say goodbye to our favorite trail dog, Avey (aka Princess Peach). She had to go home and her momma Reggie Rockets is sad. It wasn‚Äôt Reggie‚Äôs intention to have Avey out for her entire thru hike, but it still stinks- she was the loveliest trail dog, and asked to sit in my lap around the fire on her last night with us. Love her ‚ù§Ô∏è Oh, and I‚Äôm also currently in a cheap motel room in Roanoke VA, recuperating after nearly 5 days of diarrhea. I wasn‚Äôt doing myself any favors by staying on the trail, so I hopped off today and went to an urgent care for a broad spectrum antibiotic and a couple days of rest in a private room. I‚Äôm looking forward to doing some trail magic tmro afternoon for hikers near Catawba! Making the best of a (literally) shitty situation! Hope to be back on trail by Friday morning. #smidgehikestheat #appalachiantrail2018 #atthruhike2018 #atnobo2018 #possiblygiardia #butwhoknows #imtiredofshittingtho

AT Day 51- Mile 719.8
VA624 to Lamberts Meadow Shelter- 16.3 Mile Day.
Today @k.oolvibes joined me for her first ever backpacking trip in a day that included McAfee‚Äôs Knob and Tinker Cliffs. She enjoyed Dragons Tooth as part of a day hike but today was full pack and 20+ trip planned. The climb to McAfee‚Äôs was pretty easy and designed for tourist and day hikers from the VA cities. The views were worth every step even hiking through and good rain storm part of the way up. No sooner did we get to the top, did I hear ‚Äúis that backwards hat?‚Äù It was Brick! I haven‚Äôt seen him in a few days, first time we‚Äôve hiked separate since mile 140. I‚Äôm glad Kari got to meet him. Brick was pushing onto Daleville for the night as Kari and I sat and enjoyed lunch with a view. Mid afternoon, we packed up and made the climb for Tinkers. I didn‚Äôt expect the difficulty that would come with that section of trail. As we made the final mile push to the top, my calves were screaming at me. I can only imagine how hers felt. Once at the top, you walk along the cliffs and get views looking back at McAfees and the mountains you just climbed to get here. Our camp for the night was only a mile down the mountain so it was a great finish to the day. We set up camp, made dinner (hers Vegan) and relaxed to the sounds of our home for the night. We had a stream 5 feet away and birds were playing their music for us to fall asleep. I can‚Äôt wait to find out more about what @k.oolvibes thought of her first backpacking trip. Tomorrow we hike out the 10 miles to Daleville where she already made mention she wants a gourmet coffee and vegan ice cream! Trail munchies are real... she‚Äôs my favorite hiking partner #wcw #wce

AT Day 48 Mile 695.6
Laurel Creek Shelter to Trout Creek VA 620- 21.3 Mile Day- I somehow got my tent up last night before the rain came. I passed out quickly and woke up just before 3am. Normally I go back to sleep but today, my anxious self jumped up and got my day started. My ankle was tight from yesterday‚Äôs twisting and I planned to do a simple 14 Miles to a road crossing, then hitch up to Daleville. Once in Daleville, I would check into the hotel and wait for my girlfriend to arrive from Delaware. I packed up and got the hike started under dark, cloudy skies and the view of my headlamp. The temp was around 50 so made for a great early morning. The hours rolled by and so did the miles. I could notice my ankle but instead, I shifted my thoughts to other things like the anticipation of my lady‚Äôs arrival! I passed the 14 mile mark around sunrise and knew there was another road ahead 7 more miles. Onward I went without needing much water or food. In the last few miles, the overcompensation for my left ankle began to set in. My left shin started hurting, then calf felt like it was going to cramp, my knee began to throb and eventually it worked it‚Äôs way up to my left butt cheek. All of the pain was tolerable but noticeable. I finished on a gravel road and hiked out to the pave one. Once there I caught a hitch and figured my day was pretty much over. A nap at the hotel and some food was my new focus. As luck would have it, this section of actually takes a southern turn, and I was hitching on the wrong side of the road. The ride that picked me up, took me back the way I can towards Newport VA (a town with a post office and a gas station). I got dropped off an hour south of where my hotel reservations were! I grabbed a chocolate milk, Gatorade, banana and apple pie as i tried to figure out what to do. Luckily a previous Thru Hiker said she could help me out! @lindsayeclark Picked me up and drove me the 30+ miles to Daleville! THANK YOU!! #trailmagic I grabbed a coffee, BBQ, a nap and about 17 showers to try and smell not homeless. My love arrived and we had a great time catching up over a beer and fried Brussels sprouts at Ballast Point Brewery. üñ§

AT Day 43- Mile 590.2
Chestnut Knob Shelter to US52 (Bland VA) 21 Mile Day- Bacon and I woke up to a beautiful sunrise over God‚Äôs Thumbprint and were able to still see the full moon behind us over the shelter where Brick still slept. It was an awesome morning view! The 3 of us had little to no food with Brick being the lowest (1 instant mash potatoes). Bacon had some snacks and a tuna packet with mashed. I gave Brick 1 of my 2 last tuna packets and the last of the PB&J container (1/8 full). I was left with 2 nut bars, a iced sticky bun, a handful or Cheetos, 1 tortilla, and a tuna packet. Combined we had about 1500 calories each to power through 21 miles. The day started with frosted ground and temps below freezing. As we hiked, the temps reached 66 and we got sunburnt. Nothing about today‚Äôs hike was memorable or scenic. A follower on IG @superpackk reached out and said he was from Bland and amazingly offered to bring us snacks knowing we were low on food midway on trail at a gravel road crossing. He also brought apple juice!!! #trailmagic Jacob then met us 7 miles later in Bland and drove us to get groceries and DQ. As he dropped us off at the trail head, another hiker who was trying to hitch about the time we left (hour later) was still trying to get a ride in town! That would‚Äôve been us had Jacob not helped out. He even took that hiker down into town to his hotel. We ended up setting up tents right off the trail head for the night and sat on the rock cliffs as trucks drove by US 77 down below. Falling asleep to sounds of a major highway isn‚Äôt the best but I‚Äôm in my tent, no rain fly, able to look up at the stars and almost full moon. It was a good day.
Beautiful sunset and amazing times in Virginia! Everyone enjoying spring? #walktheparks #atnobo2018 #appalachiantrail #virginia #backpacking

Yesterday I celebrated one month of being on the Appalachian Trail. One month of no makeup, no hair dryer, no job, no Netflix and no responsibilities. Life at 2mph has been everything and more than I imagined it would be. The AT has brought funny, intelligent and the most interesting people into my life. I wake up stiff and go to bed sore but I have rewarding views, watch spring flowers bloom, and eat as many calories as I can get my hands on. Day 18/19 - Silers Bald Shelter to Icewater Spring Shelter, Icewater Spring Shelter to Cosby Knob Shelter, from Silers we woke before sunrise and quietly left the shelter before most people had stirred. We hiked into the rising sun up to Clingmans Dome, the highest point in the Smokies and in Tennessee. We made it up to the observation lookout and had full visibility. We even had a tourist ask to take their picture with us ü§£ it was sooo windy up there, the kind of wind that could actually blow you down! We continued on up the trail, the terrain had been changing all morning, it is looking more like the Pacific Northwest, mossy forest floor, evergreen trees, we stopped of trail for a bit and made coffee and area pot of pudding, Half Slow showed up and we hiked together for an hour, he recited Muir while we hiked and his energy kept us hiking at a quick clip, we paused at a small water source to fill a bottle and he continued on. We came out of the trail a bit later to a clearly and a small parking lot to #trailmagic hosted by #thesolesisters hiking club PERFECT TIMING, we were hungry and I‚Äôm need of some extra food. After snaking and chatting with  these trail angels we hiked on to Newfound Gap, a marker for the Tennesee NorthCarolina border line and began the second half of our time in the smokies. The park began  to feel drier and looked more like northern New Mexico and eastern Washingtonüíó we landed at Icewater Springs Shelter, where we found lots of other people and more on there way. We knew the night would be dry so we held of from the shelter until it filled up and then pitched our tent, we both sleep so much better in our tent. Close to sunset I suggested we walk up the trail to Charlie‚Äôs Bunion, we took in a stunning sunset and view of the park and had a great conversation, just the two of us taking it all in. We were both glad we had taken in the sunset , when we woke the next morning at dawn to wind and fog, visibility was low. As we hiked through the day frost formed@on the trees, wind howled and we kept moving to stay warm. Cosby Knob would be our last night Smokies #atthruhike #appalachiantrail2018 #atthruhike2018 #atnobo2018

We would have had to do over 10 miles in just a few hours. Which means an early start for us in the rain tomorrow. #chasingblazes#AT2018#appalachiantrail#appalachiantrail2018#atthruhike#thruhike2018#georgiatomaine#atnobo2018#thetrek#trektheat

DAY 16/17 - Fontana to Russell Field Shelter, Russell Field Shelter to Silers Bald Shelter, leaving Fontana Dam in the morning we felt a gentle snow begin. We hiked the day in snow fall, cold temps and gorgeous frost forest, the beginning of our week in the #gsmnp We had the joy of hiking with some trail family we have come to adore, sharing the snowy, cold and staying warm hiking. End of first day was at Russell Field with one other hiker and it got down below 20 degrees over night. next day was icy cold, but sunny and the day warmed by mid day all the snow and ice was melted away. We had some incredible view of the park and beyond through out the day. We finished the day at Silers Bald Shelter and had a full Shelter for the evening. We were fortunate to have a fellow hiker who was interested in making a fire in the shelter fireplace that evening, so we were cozy. #atthruhike #atthruhike2018 #atnobo2018 #appalachiantrail2018 #snow #smokeymountains
Made it to Damascus, VA. Trimmed some bushes at a hostel as a part of my efforts to #giveback on #walktheparks . #atnobo2018 #atthruhike #appalachiantrail #lifeisgood

DAY 14+15 - We said our goodbyes to @nantahalaoutdoorcenter and headed out in the afternoon up the steep mountainside towards Sassafras Gap Shelter. It was üåû and warm after a day off we could feel our legs working üî• We made camp at Locust Cove Gap, knowing rain was coming over night through the next day. We had a yummy dinner that night of Gnocchi and sausage and salmon. I‚Äôll post some photos of food we are enjoying as I take more picture of meals. We usually gobble them up before I even think to snap a shot. Sunday we woke up to rain, made coffee and breakfast and packed up the wet tent and hiked aalllll day in the rain. It was our longest day yet and we were soaked most of the day with rain and sweat. We only saw two other people on trail the entire day. We made it to Fontana ‚ÄúHilton‚Äù Shelter around 6 pm, and we were tired! Made food and were able to squeeze into the shelter for the evening. The rain let up once we got the Fontana and we had some time to prepare food and situate ourselves in the shelter without üí¶falling. About an hour into our night in the shelter, our trail friends ‚ÄúHalf-Slow‚Äù and ‚ÄúM+M‚Äù brought üåà‚ú®#trailmagic ‚ú®üåà to the Shelter in the form of BOJANGLES fried chicken and biscuits. üòçüçó There was much rejoicing! It was a wonderful end to a full day on the trail #atnobo2018 #atthruhike #appalachiantrail2018 #atthruhike2018 #hikeyourownhike

Over one month and 300 miles into our AT thru-hike and not a single blister *knock on wood* all thanks to our @injinji toe liners! We have seen so many people out for days due to injuries regarding their feet already. These liners are the deal breaker for us!!! They keep our feet cool and truly wick away all moisture. We wear them with a wool sock like @smartwool or @darntoughvermont , they collect the moisture and create a friction barrier to prevent blisters. Highly recommend!! #atthruhike #appalachiantrail #atnobo2018 #atthruhike2018 #hikerlife #hiketheat #noblisters #toesocksornosocks #hikinggear

Day 9 + 10 - WE HAVE HIKED OUR FIRST 100 miles! ‚õ∞üí•üôåüèº I k ow it doesn‚Äôt seem like much when you think about us hiking another 22 of those, but it feels awesome to us. We got to the top of Mt Albert yesterday, after hiking most of the day in fog and rain. The climb to the top is a class two scramble, very rocky and we couldn‚Äôt see much from the top because of fog, but we felt great getting to the top and giving @brucemfallis and @fallismarcia a call to let the know we made it üèÜ we set camp that night and washed up. We had a dry cold night, which felt great coming off several wet cold days/nights. The sun was out our tent was pretty dry and we enjoyed a day of seeing our shadows and hiking with a fellow hiker for most of the afternoon. Getting to hear other people‚Äôs stories about life, about what brought them to this journey is a part of the time I enjoy most. We learn from each other and we get to laugh together. We are ending our day atop Siler Bald, we have a 360 degree view so we should see a beautiful sunset and sunrise üèïüåÑüåÖ Can‚Äôt wait to share! #appalachiantrail2018 #eat #hike #sleep #repeat #backpack #backpacking #backpackerstory #atnobo2018 #atthruhike2018 #atthruhike #northbound #mtalbert

Day 8 - Bly Gap to Standing Indian Mountain, brrrrrr cold, wet night and morning BUT THE ICE LOOKED SO COOL THIS MORNING! We stayed in our tent a few more hours than normal this morningüå¨our tent was hard from ice. Once we got moving in the morning, the ice did, too. Raining down on us all morning, which made us laugh every time a little chunk landed on our heads. By afternoon we had a big sun break and were able to set up a line to dry out our tent and sleeping bags and eat a big lunch. We hiked on, finishing our day at this stunning overlook, view of the mountains we have been climbing this last week, full of memories üíóüíóüíóBryce and I talked today about the memories we already have made in the short time we have been out. Day 15: OMG where do I begin?! I‚Äôve never felt more at home than I do at this moment. I‚Äôve found my people. And they‚Äôre weird. Like me üòä 1) me, this morning, at The Jumpoff from Wessler Bald shelter. Hiked down into the clouds along this ridgeline for 6.5 miles. Glorious. 2) I hit the 100 mile mark on Tuesday near Mt Albert in NC. Gnarly climb up- was actually on my hands and knees at one point! Sorry Mom! 3) hopped off trail for a few hours Thursday in Franklin NC to get stove fuel and a hot meal. Walked through town and found this cemetery on my way back to the shuttle. 4) I‚Äôve been hiking with a ‚Äúbubble‚Äù on and off since I started. Purple Streak (aka Chris) was unfortunately our first casualty of the trail, succumbing to a wrist fracture while descending Unicoi Gap two Thursdays ago. I was ahead of her by a few hours and didn‚Äôt hear about her fall until two days later after getting back to the trail after Hiawassee. I was stoked to see her handing out trail magic at Rock Gap when I hopped back on after my quick stop in Franklin! Love you, girl ‚ù§Ô∏è 5) the sunrise at Siler Bald shelter yesterday. It was the start of an 18 mile day of hiking through sun, snow, sleet, and rain for 10 hours. 6) Trail Magic was off the chain at Burningtown Gap yesterday! The Green Mountain Brigade from Alabama (google them) had set up camp and was ready to feed an army. Period costumes from 1840‚Äôs, cooking biscuits and chili over an open fire...wow. So grateful for this oasis in the middle of a grinding day in shitty weather. 7) Me, again this morning at The Jumpoff. As taken by P-Dub, a retired K-6 art teacher who stayed at the same shelter last night. This descent into the clouds has been both the most exhilarating and most physically painful day yet. I can‚Äôt wait to get back to it tomorrow! üòä‚ù§Ô∏èüí™üèæ Footnote- the bivy (my shelter) has now been fully rain tested in a downpour with high winds and it is totally legit 100% waterproof üëåüèæ #smidgehikestheat #appalachiantrail2018 #atthruhike2018 #atnobo2018 #abqsolesisters #squirrelsnutbutter

Gear post 5 - Packing system

This is the majority of my stuff as I pack it into or strap it into sections of my pack. I find the Sea to Summit lightweight dry sacks to be helpful in keeping my crap organized. NOTE: I preemptively lined my green food dry sack with an oven roasting bag. I‚Äôm glad I did because the dry sack was NOT waterproof when used as directed. Contents stayed dry but there was water between the layers after hanging on a bear cable overnight with rain. I also put my yellow quilt dry sack in an oven roasting back for extra protection. Made my pot cozy from Reflectix material purchased on Amazon, and used instructions online. It works ok- I actual prefer to use it as I eat out of my pot to help keep food warm longer.
#smidgehikestheat #appalachiantrail2018 #atthruhike2018 #atnobo2018

Gear post 4 - Approximately 5 days of food

I started the trail with random crap I generally liked but wasn‚Äôt sure I‚Äôd be hungry for. I knew I wouldn‚Äôt have much of an appetite for the first week or so, so I kept it simple at first. But I am having cravings for specific things now so I‚Äôm stoked to get back out there with new food options. I also ate a gigantic medium rare loaded cheeseburger with fries today while in town. I haven‚Äôt eaten red meat in a loooong time. It was delicious. I almost licked the greasy salty plate.
I like my Luna Sandals for camp shoes, especially with Injinji socks. Heavier than the crocs I see others wearing, but I am glad I brought them.

Gear post 3: Hygiene/Safety/Utility/Luxury (zoom in or check tags for more details)

I couldn‚Äôt be happier about my water setup. I find it extremely easy to fill my 1.5 liter bag, especially since it fits nicely into an outer pocket on my pack, and the tube loops perfectly through a shoulder strap and doesn‚Äôt flip around. It‚Äôs also easy to disconnect the ‚Äúclean‚Äù tube to squeeze filtered water into my pot for cooking. I highly recommend all varieties of Squirrel‚Äôs Nut Butter- my feet are pampered, and the Born to Rub has been so helpful to relax sore muscles before bed. I am glad I brought my Kindle Fire. Reading a little breaks up the monotony of a long afternoon in camp.

#smidgehikestheat #appalachiantrail2018 #atthruhike2018 #atnobo2018

Gear post 2 - Clothing/Cooking/Comfort
The only things I‚Äôve had to buy on the trail have been a new spoon (mine snapped like a twig second day) and a belt (like a dumbass I forgot one). Love wearing my Altra Lone Peaks with the Injinii liner sock and Smartwool outer sock combo...no blisters and my feet feel great. I love to sleep in REI‚Äôs midweight long underwear, as well as their 100% merino balaclava. I really like the washable ThermaRest pillow. I‚Äôm a side sleeper and it supports me well at night. The Arc‚ÄôTeryx gore-tex shell is legit (it‚Äôs also my skiing shell). And I‚Äôm stoked that my mom mailed my Alite Monarch camp chair- been dying to chill at camp in something comfortable since I can‚Äôt sit up in my bivy.

March 27 - Day 0 - hiked the Approach Trail to Springer. The Approach trail is an additional 8.6ish mile trail leading up to the Southern Terminus of the Appalachian Trail and the original start of the AT. It was a surreal feeling that after years of dreaming about has finally come true. The day was chilly, there was a thick fog and I hardly saw any other hikers, but it made it even more magical. .
.

Yesterday was insane‚ÄîLa Copa, Harland and I, at points, were walking through waist deep snow trying to find the blazes in the 30mph snowy winds. (1) Met two AT legends yesterday‚ÄîJim Chambers (M) and Bob Peoples (R)‚ÄîThese two have maintained the trail and served thru hikers for YEARS and have the best attitude of anyone I‚Äôve ever met. The stories these guys have are unparalleled‚ÄîBob Peoples, when I asked him how many miles he‚Äôs hiked in his life, said, ‚ÄúToo many thousands‚Äù. He‚Äôs hiked trails all over the globe from Asia, Europe, Middle East, the list goes on. Both of these men are AT ‚Äúhall of famers‚Äù and it was a pleasure sitting down with them and staying at their place

You all are asking what preparations for our hike are looking like. This is five months of food ready to box up and ship of in resupply boxes. It does not constitute our entire food supply. We will stop along the way in towns to stay over night in hostels. We will find grocery store to supplement and restaurants to feed us as well. But that is not to discount the work we have put in on creating food for the trip. We purchased a used dehydrator from a kind person before leaving Seattle. Once we settled in here in Texas, I have dehydrated pounds and pounds of vegetables and meats and fruits for dinners and breakfasts. I‚Äôll share more of what that looks like soon. I am so excited to share how we have been preparing for our trip as it‚Äôs start approaches rapidly. #atnobo2018 #atthruhike #appalachiantrail #hikeyourhike
